  "prompt": "What is the electric potential at the centre of sphere?",
  "response": "The electric potential at the center of a sphere depends on several factors, including whether the sphere is **conducting or non-conducting**, and how the **charge is distributed** within the sphere. Below, I'll outline the scenarios for both **uniformly charged non-conducting spheres** and **conducting spheres**.\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Uniformly Charged Non-Conducting Sphere**\n\n**Assumptions:**\n- The sphere has a **uniform charge density**.\n- It is a **solid sphere** with radius \\( R \\) and total charge \\( Q \\).\n\n**Electric Potential at the Center (\\( V_{\\text{center}} \\)):**\n\nThe electric potential inside a uniformly charged non-conducting sphere varies with the distance from the center. At the **very center**, the potential is given by:\n\n\\[\nV_{\\text{center}} = \\frac{3kQ}{2R}\n\\]\n\n**Where:**\n- \\( k \\) is Coulomb's constant (\\( k = \\frac{1}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\approx 8.988 \\times 10^9 \\, \\text{N\u00b7m}\u00b2/\\text{C}\u00b2 \\))\n- \\( Q \\) is the total charge.\n- \\( R \\) is the radius of the sphere.\n\n**Derivation Sketch:**\nThe potential inside the sphere is found by integrating the contributions of infinitesimal charge elements from the center to the surface, taking into account the varying electric field within the sphere.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Conducting Sphere**\n\n**Assumptions:**\n- The sphere is a **conductor**.\n- Charges reside on the **surface** of the sphere.\n- The sphere has radius \\( R \\) and total charge \\( Q \\).\n\n**Electric Potential at the Center (\\( V_{\\text{center}} \\)):**\n\nFor a conducting sphere, the electric potential is the same **everywhere inside** the conductor, including at the center. The potential is equal to the potential on the surface:\n\n\\[\nV_{\\text{center}} = V_{\\text{surface}} = \\frac{kQ}{R}\n\\]\n\n**Explanation:**\nIn a conductor in electrostatic equilibrium, the electric field inside the conductor is zero, and the potential is constant throughout the conductor's volume.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Uniformly Charged Non-Conducting Sphere:** \n  \\[\n  V_{\\text{center}} = \\frac{3kQ}{2R}\n  \\]\n  \n- **Conducting Sphere:** \n  \\[\n  V_{\\text{center}} = \\frac{kQ}{R}\n  \\]\n\n**Note:** If your sphere has a different charge distribution or other specific properties, the electric potential at the center may vary. Please provide additional details if you need a more tailored explanation!",
